<article xmlns="http://www.thomasoandrews.com/xmlns/bridge">
<title>A Basic Squeeze</title>
<body>
<diagram id="start">
<hand seat="N" sp="AT" he="QJ953" di="QT872" cl="2"/>
<hand seat="W"  sp="732" he="K7642" di="3" cl="T764"/>
<hand seat="E"  sp="Q954" he="AT" di="J965" cl="853"/>
<hand seat="S" sp="KJ86" he="8" di="AK4" cl="AKQJ9"/>
</diagram>
<!--
             S: AT
             H: QJ953
             D: QT872
             C: 2

S: 732                     S: Q954
H: K7642                   H: AT
D: 3                       D: J965
C: T764                    C: 853

             S: KJ86
             H: 8
             D: AK4
             C: AKQJ9
-->
<p>
Clearly, <contract code="6N"/> is off the top two hearts. A
<contract code="6D"/> contract loses a heart and a diamond if the defense forces South to ruff a heart
at trick two.
</p><p>
But <contract code="6C"/> makes.  For example, if the defense forces South to
ruff in hearts on the second trick, declarer can simply draw trumps, which squeezes East:
<diagram original="start">
<hand seat="N" sp="AT" he="Q" di="QT87^2" cl=""/>
<hand seat="W"  sp="732" he="K76" di="3" cl="^T"/>
<hand seat="E"  sp="Q954" he="" di="J965" cl=""/>
<hand seat="S" sp="KJ86" he="" di="AK4" cl="^J"/>
</diagram>
<!--
             S: AT
             H: Q
             D: QT87*2*
             C:  - 

S: 732                     S: Q954
H: K76                     H:  - 
D: 3                       D: J965
C: *T*                     C:  - 

             S: KJ86
             H:  - 
             D: AK4
             C: *J*
-->
East, to play to the fourth round of trumps, has to keep four
spades and four diamonds, an impossibility.
</p>
</body>
